NRs are categorized in different ways varying from narrow sets focusing on raw materials to broader typologies englobing an amalgam of multidimensional services provided by natural ecosystems (Moll et al., 2005; Huysman et al., 2015; Bringezu et al., 2016; etc.). Scientific literature provides several illustrations of how resource use indicators may be categorized according to a finite set of basic resources categories (Giljum et al., 2011; Bringezu et al., 2016). The resource typology developed in this study is inspired from EC (2011), Huysman et al. (2015), Giljum et al. (2011), BioIS (2012) and Baedeker et al. (2015). Applying these typologies directly would not have provided an accurate description of the GE indicators sample due to the large number of indicators with a more general focus. Therefore, the NR typology developed consists of the following twelve categories:

                                 •

Abiotic Materials (minerals, metals, ores, and fossil fuels);


                                 •

Biotic Materials (crops, livestock, fish, timber and biomass);


                                 •

Unspecific Materials (indicators relating to more than three materials indistinctly);


                                 •

Water (freshwater and seawater);


                                 •

Air;


                                 •

Land and Soil;


                                 •

Biodiversity;


                                 •

Abiotic Renewable Energy Resources (solar, wind, hydrological, geothermal sources, etc.);


                                 •

Unspecific Energy Resources (indicators relating to more than three energy resources indistinctly);


                                 •

Unspecific Resources (indicators relating to more than three resources indistinctly);


                                 •

NA (indicators not related to any of the resources listed above).

The MONET project is an initiative aiming to set up a system of indicators which could be used to measure sustainable development in Switzerland (SFSO, 2004). The indicator classification developed is similar to the DPSIR framework (EEA, 1999), but is not tailored to environmental applications and therefore applicable to social and economic topics. The MONET approach is based on the six following types of indicators:

                                 •

Level (L): measures the extent to which a need is met and not the continuous consumption of resources required for that purpose;


                                 •

Capital (C): estimates stocks and their accumulation or decline, but not consumption;


                                 •

Input/Output (Δ): relates to continuous consumption flows;


                                 •

Structural criteria:

                                          ○

Efficiency subcategory (S₁): describes consumption in relation to the result, but never as an absolute value;


                                          ○

Disparity subcategory (S₂): demonstrates distributions, but never average values for the total population;





                                 •

Response (R): relates to institutional measures taken in response to an undesirable development.

As noted earlier, GE indicators largely refer to NRs. However, this link is most often unspecific: 40.92% calibrated indicators are indistinctly related to more than 3 NR categories. Hence, while these indicators have a link with NRs or with some aspects of them (e.g. availability, affordability, quality, related impacts, etc.), they do not explicitly refer to a limited number of specific resources. Some examples are “environmental protection expenditure”, “ecological footprint” or “green trade”. As far as the remaining resource categories, several points seem worth noting:

                              •

Among NRs, GE measurement frameworks pay special attention to materials. As may be seen in Fig. 3, indicators specifically referring to abiotic materials, biotic materials and unspecific materials cover altogether 10.09% calibrated indicators. Within this resource category, we may also underline that biotic materials (6.02%) are represented three times as much as abiotic materials (1.62%);


                              •

Energy resources are also frequently referred to: unspecific energy resources and abiotic renewable energy resources account for 8.77% calibrated indicators. Some indicators categorized as dealing with biotic materials are also related to energy resources (e.g. “technical bioenergy potential from residues”);


                              •

According to our results, water (7.96%) is also frequently referred to in our sample and draws more attention than other resources such as land & soil (6.01%), air (4.80%) or biodiversity (4.71%);


                              •

All specific resource categories are missing in at least one measurement framework. Abiotic materials are the most frequently ignored one (no indicator refers to it in five different frameworks). Abiotic renewable energy resources 
                                 on the other hand, while accounting for only 1.92% calibrated indicators, are missing in just one framework.

                           Fig. 4 also shows that, according to the definition of resources adopted, the category Unspecific Resources is very broad. This category draws most of indicators also referring to SDGs 8, 9, 12, 13 and 16. To better understand the links between unspecific resources and the SDGs, a new typology made of eleven subcategories was created and subsequently applied. The typology was inductively developed by the research team through keywords identification:

                                 •

Human Resources;


                                 •

Macroeconomic Data;


                                 •

R&D - Innovation;


                                 •

Infrastructures;


                                 •

Waste and Recycling;


                                 •

Private Financial Resources;


                                 •

Green Sector and Sustainable Practices;


                                 •

Risk and Vulnerability;


                                 •

Public Measures;


                                 •

GHG Emissions;


                                 •

Others.
